# Conciseness & Clarity

Sources: Draft.dev Style Guide, Elastic Docs Style Guide, Refactoring English

## Sentence Length

- Target **under 25 words** per sentence. Split longer sentences.
- One idea per sentence. If a sentence has "and" joining two unrelated clauses, split it.

## Paragraph Length

- Keep paragraphs **under 7 lines**. Dense walls of text lose readers.
- Break at logical boundaries — a new concept or step deserves a new paragraph.

## Word Choice — Prefer Simple

| Avoid | Prefer |
|-------|--------|
| utilize | use |
| in order to | to |
| assist | help |
| attempt | try |
| commence | start / begin |
| terminate | end / stop |
| subsequent | next |
| prior to | before |
| facilitate | help / enable |
| leverage | use |

## Words to Avoid in Technical Prose

- **"easy" / "simple" / "straightforward" / "trivial"** — these invalidate readers who find it hard. State what it does, not how hard it is.
- **"just"** — implies the step is obvious. Cut it.
- **"obviously" / "clearly" / "of course"** — if it were obvious, you wouldn't need to write it.

```markdown
<!-- BAD -->
You can simply configure the DMA by just passing the shape descriptor.
This is straightforward — obviously, the kernel needs a tile size.

<!-- GOOD -->
Configure the DMA by passing the shape descriptor.
The kernel requires a tile size.
```

## Eliminate Redundancy

- Do not repeat the same concept in consecutive sentences with different wording.
- Each paragraph must add new information. If removing a paragraph changes nothing, remove it.

## Put Conditions Before Instructions

```markdown
<!-- BAD -->
Run `make test` if you want to verify the build.

<!-- GOOD -->
To verify the build, run `make test`.
```
